commit.message:
feat: Add Django 3.0 support (#94)

* Use django.utils.render() instead of render_ro_response()

Removed in django 3.0

See: https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/3.0/releases/3.0/#features-removed-in-3-0

* Use six package instead of vendored django.utils.six

Removed in django 3.0

See: https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/3.0/releases/3.0/#removed-private-python-2-compatibility-apis

* Add django 3.0 to Travis CI matrix

* Address review comments

render() does not take a context_instance variable, it can safely be omitted.

Co-Authored-By: Stavros Korokithakis <hi@stavros.io>

Isinstance Merging and Code Formatting (#89)

* isinstance merging

* code formatting

Drop support for Django < 1.11 and remove workarounds (#87)

Per Django's recommendation, now that django-annoying supports 2.0, it
should drop support for Django < 1.11 to ease maintenance and
compatibility across Django versions. So long as no deprecation warnings
are produced, django-annoying should remain forward compatible with the
next Django version.

For more details, see the Django docs:

https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/2.0/releases/2.0/#third-party-library-support-for-older-version-of-django

> Third-party library support for older version of Django
>
> Following the release of Django 2.0, we suggest that third-party app authors
> drop support for all versions of Django prior to 1.11. At that time, you
> should be able to run your package’s tests using python -Wd so that
> deprecation warnings do appear. After making the deprecation warning fixes,
> your app should be compatible with Django 2.0.

commit.message:
Add testing and support for Django 2.0 (#83)

No actual code changes were required.
doc: Note MySQL native JSONField exists too (#82)

Introduce isort to automatically sort import order (#75)

Removes the need for contributors to give any thought to how to organize
import statements. Can simply let the tools handle it instead.

Use same configuration as used by the Django project.

Add isort check to Travis configuration.
Drop support for Python 3.2 (#80)
Add Django as a requirement in setup.py (#76)

Include license file in the generated wheel package (#74)

The wheel package format supports including the license file. This is
done using the [metadata] section in the setup.cfg file. For additional
information on this feature, see:

https://wheel.readthedocs.io/en/stable/index.html#including-the-license-in-the-generated-wheel-file

fix: Officially deprecate signals (#77)

It duplicates Django functionality of receiver decorator:

https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/1.11/topics/signals/#connecting-receiver-functions

After a release, can remove the functionality.
Clean up trailing white space in README.md (#78)
fix: Officially deprecate autostrip in favor of Django's implementation (#79)

doc: Removed mentions of Python 2.6. (#73)

Support of Python 2.6 is deprecated in
20ef6de12d7fb1532b441031230b3bef4b4a3c01.
doc: Mention built-in JSONField for Postgres (#72)

docs: add syntax highlighting on code samples (#71)

Also remove the escaping of underscores inside h3 titles.

Rename [wheel] section to [bdist_wheel] as the former is legacy (#70)

See:

https://bitbucket.org/pypa/wheel/src/54ddbcc9cec25e1f4d111a142b8bfaa163130a61/wheel/bdist_wheel.py?fileviewer=file-view-default#bdist_wheel.py-119:125

http://pythonwheels.com/
Run flake8 on Travis CI (#69)
Add testing for Django 1.11 and Python 3.6 (#68)
feat: Allow serializer customization for JSONField (#53) (#65)

Enable universal wheel support (#66)

http://pythonwheels.com/
